{{Infobox legislation |short_title = Financial Market Infrastructure Act |legislature = [[Federal Assembly (Switzerland)|Federal Assembly]] of [[Switzerland]] |date_enacted = January 1, 2016 |date_passed = June 19, 2015 |status = Current }}
The '''Financial Market Infrastructure Act''' ('''FMIA'''), original title ''Finanzmarktinfrastrukturgesetz'' ('''FinfraG''') is a body of [[Law of Switzerland|Swiss legislation]] for the regulation of financial markets, in particular [[Derivative (finance)|derivatives]]. It was originally adopted by the Swiss [[Federal Assembly (Switzerland)|Federal Assembly]] on June 19, 2015 and came into force on January 1, 2016.
The objective of the legislation is to reduce [[systemic risk|systemic]] counterparty and operational risk, and help prevent future financial system collapses. FMIA is intended as the Swiss equivalent to the regulatory packages in the U.S. and the European Union, such as [[Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act|Dodd–Frank]] and [[European Market Infrastructure Regulation|EMIR]] / [[Markets in Financial Instruments Directive 2004|MiFID]], respectively.
The FMIA regulations include requirements for reporting of derivative contracts and implementation of risk management standards. It also established common rules for central [[counterparty|counterparties]] and [[Trade Repository|trade repositories]]. The implementation of FMIA is overseen by [[Swiss Financial Market Supervisory Authority|FINMA]].
